<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41707480</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>07</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>07</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1873-1600</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>78</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Mar</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Physical therapy in sport : official journal of the Association of Chartered Physiotherapists in Sports Medicine</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Phys Ther Sport</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>High previous-week training load amplifies hip adduction squeeze strength reductions in male academy football players with performance-limiting groin pain.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>101902</StartPage><MedlinePgn>101902</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.ptsp.2026.101902</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S1466-853X(26)00023-4</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="OBJECTIVE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">To examine whether preceding seven-day football training load and previous seven-day groin pain influence hip adduction squeeze strength in academy football players.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="DESIGN" NlmCategory="METHODS">Longitudinal observational study with twice weekly repeated measures over seven weeks.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="SETTING" NlmCategory="METHODS">West African academy football club.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="PARTICIPANTS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Nineteen male academy football players (age 16.5&#xa0;&#xb1;&#xa0;0.9 [15-18] years).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="MAIN OUTCOME MEASURES" NlmCategory="METHODS">Hip adduction squeeze strength, performance-limiting groin pain, and football training load were captured. Observations with and without groin pain were stratified into two groups, and two linear-mixed effects models examined hip adduction squeeze strength based on preceding-week football training load.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Hip adduction squeeze strength was significantly influenced by football training load when associated with groin pain (estimate -0.13, 95% CI [-0.20, -0.07], p&#xa0;&lt;&#xa0;0.001). In observations without groin pain, football training load did not influence hip adduction squeeze strength (estimate -0.01, 95% CI [-0.06, 0.03], p&#xa0;=&#xa0;0.634.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">When groin pain is present, hip adduction squeeze strength is adversely influenced by higher football training loads. Players without groin pain do not experience hip adduction squeeze strength reductions from high football training load. Monitoring training load should be a consideration for practitioners working with football players that are experiencing groin pain.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>DeLang</LastName><ForeName>Matthew D</ForeName><Initials>MD</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Human Performance Department, Right to Dream, Old Akrade, Ghana; Human Performance Department, Right to Dream, Farum, Denmark. Electronic address: mdel@fcn.dk.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Ish&#xf8;i</LastName><ForeName>Lasse</ForeName><Initials>L</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Human Performance Department, Right to Dream, Farum, Denmark; Sports Orthopedic Research Center - Copenhagen (SORC-C), Department of Orthopedic Surgery, Hvidovre Hospital, Copenhagen, Denmark.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Thornton</LastName><ForeName>Kasper</ForeName><Initials>K</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Human Performance Department, Right to 